<!-- BEGIN ARTICLE HTML -->


<div id="aueditable"><!--DO NOT MODIFY THIS LINE AND ABOVE-->

<p>
 <a href="//plato.stanford.edu/info.html#takedown"><img alt="Engraving of Hartley" src="hartley.jpg" /></a>
 <br />
<em>Engraving by William Blake, 1791</em></p>

<h1>David Hartley</h1><div id="pubinfo"><em>First published Mon Nov 25, 2002; substantive revision Thu Sep 4, 2025</em></div>

<div id="preamble">

<p>
David Hartley (1705&ndash;57) is the author of <em>Observations on
Man, his Frame, his Duty, and his Expectations</em> (1749)&mdash;a
synthesis of neurology, psychology, and spirituality.</p>

<p>
As science, the <em>Observations</em> grounds consciousness in
neurophysiology, mind in brain. On this basis, the central concept of
&ldquo;association,&rdquo; much discussed by other British
philosophers and psychologists, receives distinctive treatment: the
term first names the physiological processes that generate
&ldquo;ideas&rdquo; and then the psychological processes by which
perceptions, thoughts, and emotions either link and fuse or break
apart. In keeping with this approach, Hartley offers a novel account
of how we learn and perform skilled actions, a dimension of human
nature often left unexplored in works of philosophy. Such actions
include those involved in speech&mdash;and, by extension, the conduct
of scientific inquiry.</p>

<p>
Central to the moral psychology is a typology of six emotional
schemas: Imagination, Ambition, Self-Interest, Sympathy, Theopathy,
and the Moral Sense. Taken together, the six schemas form a picture of
human beings driven, and guided, by what they experience as
&ldquo;intellectual&rdquo; pleasures and pains. The six are
generative, as, for example, Imagination &ldquo;models&rdquo; (in the
sense of shapes or forms) Ambition, and also cybernetic, as Sympathy
&ldquo;new models&rdquo; Self-Interest. The picture is dynamic and
teleological. For example, a person whose &ldquo;primary
pursuit&rdquo; is Ambition will find the pursuit itself inevitably
leads to both satisfaction and discontent. The inability of Ambition
to solve the problem it creates thus pushes the person onward to a
hedonic economics, Self-Interest, and then, when the problems
generated by the pursuit of Self-Interest also prove insoluble,
potentially toward a further reorientation of one&rsquo;s
&ldquo;primary pursuit&rdquo; in a new sense of self grounded in
Sympathy&mdash;which in turn leads the person to re-evaluate what
truly counts as self-interest.</p>

<p>
Regarding our &ldquo;expectations,&rdquo; Hartley imagines that in
&ldquo;the true system of things &hellip; the voice of nature is an
universal chorus of joy and transport,&rdquo; and that within it our
&ldquo;expectations&rdquo; can rest upon the assurance of universal
salvation: all people will eventually become &ldquo;partakers of the
divine nature, loving and lovely, holy and happy&rdquo; (<em>OM</em>
2, prop. 56). In this regard, the <em>Observations</em> presents an
original model of spiritual growth, which describes how the self both
forms and transforms as the person gains in Sympathy and
Theopathy&mdash;put simply, learns to love, both others and God.</p>

<p>
Hartley&rsquo;s synthesis rests on two core concepts:
&ldquo;philosophical necessity&rdquo; and divine causality. Given the
&ldquo;previous circumstances of body and mind&rdquo; that form the
nexus of the present moment, &ldquo;a person cannot do indifferently
of the actions <em>A,</em> and its contrary <em>a</em>&rdquo;
(<em>OM</em> 1, Conclusion). Nonetheless, &ldquo;since God is the
cause of all things, &hellip; he must be the cause of all the motions
in the material world&rdquo; (<em>OM</em> 1, prop. 30). Together, the
two provided assurance for people committed to religious and social
reform. We live, as it were, as fish in a sea of physical, social, and
cognitive events, but a sea radiant with light. Clear the water and
the light will shine through.</p>

<p>
The son of an Anglican clergyman, David Hartley was born in June 1705
in the vicinity of Halifax, Yorkshire. His mother died three months
after his birth, and his father when David was fifteen. After
receiving his B.A. and M.A. from Jesus College, Cambridge, Hartley
practiced medicine in Bury St. Edmunds (1730&ndash;35), London
(1735&ndash;42), and Bath, where he died on 28 August 1757. He married
twice: in 1730, Alice Rowley, who died in 1731 giving birth to their
son David (1731&ndash;1813); and in 1735, Elizabeth Packer
(1713&ndash;78), despite the opposition of her wealthy family. The
couple had two children, Mary (1736&ndash;1803) and Wincombe Henry
(1740&ndash;94). Although severely afflicted with bladder stones,
Hartley lived a full and active life: he practiced medicine, engaged
in mathematical research, sought a cure for &ldquo;the stone,&rdquo;
devoted himself to intellectual and philanthropic projects, and wrote
the <em>Observations on Man.</em> Two days after the event, <em>London
Evening Post</em> noted: &ldquo;His Death is much lamented by the
Poor.&rdquo;</p>
</div> 

<div id="toc"><!--Entry Contents-->
